{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18423"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18423"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11141"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114254"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11141"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"},{"type":"tags","id":"10290"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114254"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is correct regarding muscle twitches and their influence on muscle fibre tension?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Twitches result in sustained muscle contraction","Twitches require multiple action potentials to occur","Twitches are produced by a single action potential","Twitches are the primary mechanism for muscle fatigue","Twitches are usually strong and useful for muscle activity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitches are produced by a single action potential\u003C/strong\u003E, leading to a brief contraction of the muscle fibre. This is the basic unit of muscle contraction. While a single twitch is not strong or useful for sustained activity, repeated stimulation can lead to summation, where the muscle does not fully relax between stimuli, increasing tension and leading to a stronger contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitches result in sustained muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because a single twitch is a brief contraction and does not sustain muscle tension. Sustained contraction requires repeated stimuli and summation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitches are usually strong and useful for muscle activity\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as twitches are generally weak and not useful for significant muscle activity. They are the building blocks for more complex contractions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitches require multiple action potentials to occur\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because a single action potential is sufficient to produce a twitch. Multiple action potentials lead to summation and tetanus, not individual twitches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitches are the primary mechanism for muscle fatigue\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as muscle fatigue is a complex process involving energy depletion, ion imbalances, and other factors, not just the occurrence of twitches.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Muscle twitches are brief contractions resulting from a single action potential.","The frequency of stimulation can influence muscle tension by summation of twitches.","Twitches are generally not strong or useful for sustained muscle activity."],"references":["Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18423"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:17:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:17:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11141"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114254"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and re